Linear Regression

Everything You Need to Know

Nick Broussard

04 February 2020

Hello!!

Welcome to this tutorial on multiple linear regression!

Linear regression is statistical tool used to test hypothesis about the influence of certain variables (predictors) on another (outcome). The null hypothesis states that variables do not affect on each other, wheareas the alternate hypothesis states that the variables do affect each other.

\(\ h_{0}\): Variables do not affect each other \(\ h_{a}\): Variables do affect each other

If we get significant model predictors then well reject the null hypothesis. Otherwise, we fail to reject the null hypothesis. Significance means that a given effect is super rare - so rare in fact that its highly unlikely wed see that effect if it wasnt real.

Data comes from the City of Austins Open Data Portal. Were looking at Energy Conservation Audit and Disclosure (ECAD) data [(found here)](here. I want to examine how average monthly energy use in kWh is effected by a multifamily residential buildings year of construction, size in sft, attic insulation (R-value), and number of floors.

Expore and Clean

First, read in the dataset.

#Download from my GitHub folder.
df <- fread("https://raw.githubusercontent.com/nicholasbroussard/tutorials/master/linear.multiple_ecad_austin.csv", stringsAsFactors = F)

Second, select the variables of interest and rename.

df <- df %>%
  select("Average Monthly kWh", "ECAD Year Built", "Average Apt Size", "ECAD R Value", "ECAD Number of Floors") %>%
  #Let's the variables easier-to-read names.
  setnames(old = c("Average Monthly kWh", "ECAD Year Built", "Average Apt Size", "ECAD R Value", "ECAD Number of Floors"),
           new = c("Energy",  "YearBuilt", "Size", "RValue", "Floors"))

Third, check variable types

df$YearBuilt <- as.numeric(as.character(df$YearBuilt))

Lots of variance, which violates the assumption of homoscedasticity. Read more here.

Scale variables in the model.

Model

First, split the data.

set.seed(101)
sample <- sample.split(df, SplitRatio = .7)
train <- subset(df, sample == T)
test <- subset(df, sample == F)

Some folks disagree with data-splitting. Check out this Quora thread for more info.

Second, run and interpret the regression.

set.seed(101)
model <- lm(Energy ~ ., data = train)
summ(model,
     confint = T,
     scale = T, 
     vifs = T) #Variable Inflation Factors
Observations 836
Dependent variable Energy
Type OLS linear regression
F(5,830) 85.35
R 0.34
Adj. R 0.34
Est. 2.5% 97.5% t val. p VIF
(Intercept) 565.10 542.11 588.10 48.23 0.00 NA
YearBuilt 31.65 17.57 45.72 4.41 0.00 1.76
Size 90.12 78.09 102.14 14.71 0.00 1.28
RValue 2.22 -9.89 14.33 0.36 0.72 1.30
Floors2 -3.59 -32.44 25.26 -0.24 0.81 1.32
Floors3 28.20 -3.63 60.02 1.74 0.08 1.32
Standard errors: OLS; Continuous predictors are mean-centered and scaled by 1 s.d.

Model: \(\ y=547+26*YearBuilt+95*Size-3.5*RValue+5*2ndFloor+44*3rdFloor\).

Interpretation:

  • Dependent Variable
    • 1st floor unit energy use is \(\ 547kWh \over month\) (\(\ y=547\)).
  • Independent Variables
    • 1 year decrease in age is associated with increased energy use of \(\ 26kWh \over month\). Specifically, a 1st floor unit thats 1 year newer than another unit is expected to use \(\ 573kWh \over month\) (\(\ y=547+26*1\)).
    • 1 sft increase in size is associated with increased energy use of \(\ 95kWh \over month\) after controlling for all other variables. Specifically, a 1st floor unit thats 1 sft bigger than the average unit is expected to use \(\ 642kWh \over month\) (\(\ y=547+95*1\)).
    • 1 unit increase in R-value thickness is associated with decreased energy use of \(\ 3.5kWh \over month\) after controlling for all other variables. Specifically, a 1st floor unit that has 1-unit thicker R-value than the average unit would use \(\ 550.5kWh \over month\) (\(\ y=547+3.5*1\)).
    • Going from the 1st floor to the second floor is associated with increased energy use of \(\ 5kWh \over month\) after controlling for all other variables. Specifically, a unit thats on the 2nd floor but otherwise has the same characteristics as the average unit would use \(\ 552kWh \over month\) (\(\ y=547+5*1\)).
    • Going from the 1st floor to the 3rd floor is associated with increased energy use of \(\ 44kWh \over month\) after controlling for all other variables. Specifically, a unit thats on the 3rd floor but otherwise has the same characteristics as the average unit would use \(\ 591kWh \over month\) (\(\ y=547+44*1\)).

and look at influential values.

ols_plot_cooksd_chart(model)

Examine influential rows individually and remove as needed.

Fourth, pull in fitted and residual values

train$Residuals <- model$residuals
train$Fitted <- model$fitted.values

and query the model.

  • Whats predicted energy use for homes built in 1981?
    YearBuilt mean(Fitted)
    1.98e+03 558
    kWh/month.
  • Whats the predicted energy use of a 2nd floor unit larger than 600 sft?
    mean(Fitted)
    580
    kWh/month

But answers are only as reliable as the model.

Fifth, evaluate goodness of fit.

Start with the baseline metrics

  • R Squared: 34%
  • Adjusted R Squared: 34%
  • Root Mean Squared Error (RMSE): 156

then look at residuals. Check for normality

ggplot(train, aes(x = model$residuals)) +
  geom_histogram(bins = 35, color = "black", fill = "cadetblue", alpha = .7) +
  theme_bw()

and the scatter of residuals against predictions.

ggplot(train, aes(x=Fitted, y=Residuals)) +
  geom_point() +
  geom_smooth(method = "lm")

The distribution shows (1) centering on 0, and (2) a degree of scattering [that] is the same for all fitted values. Therefore theres no indication of autocorrelation.

Sixth, and last, check the models performance with test data. Compare RMSEs.

test$Fitted <- predict(model, newdata = test)
df %>%
  summarise("Train Set RMSE" = round(rmse(train$Energy, train$Fitted), digits = 2), "Test Set RMSE" = round(rmse(test$Energy, test$Fitted), digits=2))
Train Set RMSE Test Set RMSE
156 157

The train RMSE is lower the test RMSE. No indication of overfitting.

Compare

Run an interactive model to compare against the first model.

First, graphically analyze the effects of predictor varibales on each other. Here, we focus on Size.

a <- interact_plot(model, pred = Size, modx = YearBuilt, plot.points = T, interval = T)
b <- interact_plot(model, pred = Size, modx = RValue, plot.points = T, interval = T)
c <- interact_plot(model, pred = Size, modx = Floors, plot.points = T, interval = T) #Categorical variable.
d <- interact_plot(model, pred = Size, modx = RValue, mod2 = Floors) #3-way interaction.

gridExtra::grid.arrange(a,b,c,d)

Parallel lines indicate that there is no interaction effect while different slopes suggest that one might be present.

Second, run and interpret a model to test the graphical output.

set.seed(101)
model2 <- lm(Energy ~ YearBuilt + Size + RValue + Floors + Size:YearBuilt, data = train)
summ(model2, scale = T, confint = T, digits = 2, vifs = T)
Observations 836
Dependent variable Energy
Type OLS linear regression
F(6,829) 73.53
R 0.35
Adj. R 0.34
Est. 2.5% 97.5% t val. p VIF
(Intercept) 575.09 551.38 598.80 47.61 0.00 NA
YearBuilt 39.33 24.53 54.13 5.22 0.00 1.97
Size 90.51 78.54 102.47 14.85 0.00 1.28
RValue 0.73 -11.35 12.81 0.12 0.91 1.31
Floors2 -5.48 -34.20 23.24 -0.37 0.71 1.33
Floors3 23.51 -8.28 55.29 1.45 0.15 1.33
YearBuilt:Size -17.77 -28.87 -6.67 -3.14 0.00 1.19
Standard errors: OLS; Continuous predictors are mean-centered and scaled by 1 s.d.

Model: \(\ y = 554 + 29*YearBuilt + 96*Size - 4*RValue + 3.5*2ndFloor + 44*3rdFloor - 15.87*Size:DuctLeakage\)

The coefficients of the individual predictors are called main effects. For interaction models, "a significant interaction term means uncertainty about the relative importance of main effects.

Interpretation:

  • Dependent Variable
    • The average energy use is \(\ 554kWh \over month\) ($y=554 $).
  • Interaction variables.
    • The effect of YearBuilt on Energy decreases by $15.87kWh month $ for every 1-unit increase in RValue.
    • Likewise, the effect of YearBuilt on Energy decreases by $15.87kWh month $ for every 1 additional year.

Stick with the first model, even with the low goodness of fit measures. For now.
